  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThe article argues that when teams need a reliable, low‑risk workflow for creating release tags, squash‑merge should be preferred over interactive rebase. It contrasts the two mental models—rebasing to rewrite history versus merging to combine whole branches—and shows how rebasing can lead to endless conflict cycles, loss of PR comments, and fragile permalinks, while squash‑merge preserves existing commits, requires fewer steps, and keeps collaboration tools intact. The piece is written for software engineers and team leads who manage Git workflows, adopting a pragmatic, slightly tongue‑in‑cheek tutorial tone that repeatedly frames the debate as a “deathmatch” and uses metaphors of “absolute power,” “black‑belt git fu,” and “engineering theater” to illustrate the stakes.",
